{[show S]When partner doubles the opponents' opening and their side raises, a double back is responsive: it shows the values and shape to compete without one clear bid of your own.
[BID X] ⟦The opponent on your left opens 1\H and your partner doubles for takeout. Their partner raises to 2\H, cramping you with a singleton in their suit. You double. This is responsive, not penalty, showing the other major and both minors with enough to compete, and it asks partner to choose our fit.⟧ Partner reads the message and bids 2\S.
[BID Pass] ⟦Partner has chosen spades from the places you offered, and with your values already shown there is nothing to add.⟧ The opener presses on to 3\H.
[BID Pass] ⟦You have shown your hand, partner picked spades, and three of a major their way is nothing to double, so you let it go.⟧ Three hearts rolls home for their part score.
[show NESW]The responsive double found the spade fit and kept you out of a phantom save. Their three hearts makes, but two spades your way was also going nowhere, so quietly conceding a small minus was the sound result.}
