{[show S]The responsive double promises the other major and both minors, so when you hold four of that major yourself, naming it is the whole point of the convention.
[BID X] ⟦The opponent on your right opens 1\H and you double for takeout with four spades and support for the minors.⟧ Their partner raises to 2\H, and your partner answers with a responsive double, showing the other major and both minors and asking you to pick the strain.
[BID 2S] ⟦Their partner passes it back to you. Partner promised four spades and you are looking at four good spades, so the 4-4 fit is certain. Name it at the cheapest level and buy the hand in your best strain.⟧ Opener competes to 3\H.
[BID Pass] ⟦You have already named the fit at the level your modest values justify; whether to push higher is partner's decision, so you pass.⟧ Partner, trusting the fit, presses on to 3\S.
[BID Pass] ⟦Partner has taken the fit to the three level, which is as high as our modest values want to go, and three of a major their way is nothing to double. You have shown your hand, so you pass it out.⟧ Three spades brings home nine tricks for a plus.
[show NESW]South read the responsive double for exactly what it promised and named the guaranteed spade fit. Buying the contract in your own 4-4 fit and taking the plus was the textbook payoff.}
