{[show S]When partner doubles the opponents' opening and their side raises, a double back is responsive: it shows the values and shape to compete without one clear bid of your own.
[BID X] ⟦The opponent on your left opens 1\H and your partner doubles for takeout. Their partner raises to 2\H. With a singleton heart, four spades, and both minors, you double. This is responsive, showing the other major and both minors with enough to compete, and it asks partner to name our fit.⟧ Before partner can answer, the opener jumps to 4\H, and they are vulnerable.
[BID 4S] ⟦Your responsive double promised four spades, so with partner's takeout double you have found an eight-card spade fit. They are bidding a vulnerable game; if it makes, defending costs you a large minus. Saving in 4\S should go only one or two down, far cheaper than their game, so you take out insurance.⟧ [ACCEPT Pass] Their partner doubles your 4\S, and partner has nothing more to say.
[BID Pass] ⟦Partner did not pull the double, so this is our chosen resting place. You accept the penalty double and play it out, expecting the save to pay off.⟧ Four spades doubled comes home for down one.
[show NESW]Down one doubled was a hundred against their vulnerable game, a clear win at the table. Reading the responsive double as an eight-card spade fit turned a likely large minus into a cheap, profitable sacrifice.}
