{[show S]When partner's responsive double promises a fit but the opponents have a game, the last decision is whether to save in your fit or take the sure defensive tricks; short trumps argue for defending.
[BID X] ⟦The opponent on your left opens 1\H and you double for takeout, short in hearts with the side suits covered. Their partner raises to 2\H.⟧ You make the standard takeout double and wait for partner. Partner comes in with a responsive double, showing the other major and both minors and asking you to place the contract.
[BID Pass] ⟦Their partner jumps to 4\H. You hold only three spades, so any spade contract is a possible 4-3 fit, and your thirteen points are full of defensive values. Rather than commit to a save, pass the decision to partner, who knows the two-suited shape.⟧ Partner takes the push and sacrifices in 4\S.
[BID Pass] ⟦Partner has chosen to save at the four level. With three trumps and defense you might have doubled 4\H instead, but partner has the shape and the minors, so you respect the save and pass.⟧ The opponent on your right doubles. [ACCEPT X]
[BID Pass] ⟦The double is theirs to make, and pulling now would only guess again at the five level with nowhere better to go, so you sit.⟧ Four spades doubled comes home with only seven tricks, a costly number against a game they were only making.
[show NESW]With three spades and a defensive thirteen, South's plus lay in defending 4\H, and passing partner's save let it become a minus. When your trumps are short opposite a promised fit, taking the defensive tricks usually beats the sacrifice.}
[Note "1:Responsive double"]
